[[File:Double-six-dice.jpg|thumb|Two dice, showing two sixes, or ''boxcars'']] '''Boxcars''', also known as '''Midnight''', is the outcome of rolling the [[dice]] in a game of [[craps]] and getting a 6 on each die. The pair of 6 pips resembles a pair of [[boxcar]]s on a freight train. In modern parlance, it refers to such a roll in any game involving 6 sided dice which are marked with pips. The probability of this roll is 1 in 36, or about 2.8%. This is the same probability as for rolling any other specific ordered pair with the dice.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dupree | first = Stephen | authorlink = |author2=S. K. Fraley | title = A Monte Carlo Primer: A Practical Approach to Radiation Transport | publisher = Springer | date = 2004 | location = | pages = 1–2 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_AGqaIuYfHQC&pg=PA2&dq=Boxcars+dice#PPP1,M1 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-306-48503-9 }}</ref>
==Probability== Rolling two 6-sided dice 25 times gives a probability of 0.505532 that at least once, Boxcars will appear.<ref>{{cite book | last = Weisstein | first = Eric | authorlink = | title = CRC Concise Encyclopedia of Mathematics | publisher = CRC Press | date = 2003 | location = | pages = 276 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_8TyhSqHUiEC&pg=PA276&dq=Boxcars+dice#PPA369,M1 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-1-58488-347-0 }}</ref> :<math>{1-} \left ( \dfrac{35}{36} \right ) ^{25} \approx 0.505532 </math>
==Betting== One of the 4 bets on any common craps table. It is on the 'high side' of the horn bet in which the player can either bet on the 2, 3, 11, or 12. When the player throws in money and calls out "midnight" or "Boxcars", the dealer will usually 'book' the bet as a bet on the 12, so as to not create confusion.
==See also== *[[Craps]] *[[Snake eyes]] *[[Yo-leven]]
